# SECTION 1: Global Content (all topics, worldwide)

## Tier 1: Score 8–10 (your highest interests — rank these first)

### [Topic A — e.g. "AI tooling & open source"]
- Concrete sub-interest 1 (e.g. "LLM inference optimization, quantization, edge deployment")
- Concrete sub-interest 2 (e.g. "Open-weight models — releases, fine-tuning, evals")
- Examples of what scores 10 here:
- Examples of what scores 6 here (and why it isn't a 10):

### [Topic B — e.g. "Frontier science & engineering"]
- ...
- ...

### [Topic C — e.g. "Indie hackers & small bets"]
- ...

## Tier 2: Score 5–7 (interested, not obsessed)

- Topics you'll read on a slow day but won't go out of your way for.
- Adjacent fields, follow-up reading, secondary signals.

## Tier 3: Score 0–4 (avoid)

- Topics you actively don't want surfaced. Be explicit — the ranker uses
  these as negative anchors.
- E.g. "celebrity tech drama, hype cycles, executive turnover gossip,
  generic SaaS marketing".

---

# SECTION 2: [Your Region] Bonus (+1.5 to local content)

Items relevant to your country/region get a score bonus so local context
surfaces. Delete this section if you don't want regional weighting.

- Local ecosystem signals (companies, research labs, policy)
- Regional events, launches, releases
- Language/culture-specific sources

---

# Notes for the ranker

- Tier ordering is the only contract that matters. Score the item against
  the closest tier description.
- When in doubt, ask: "would [Your Name] open this in a new tab?" If yes,
  ≥5. If they'd read it end-to-end, ≥8.
- Penalize: clickbait, press-release rewrites, hype without evidence.
